pr_body:
I would like to be able to filter the data in a table in more ways than just 'contains', like st-search does. Further more I would like to be able to filter different columns with different filter behaviors. For instance a column with a standard search, then a column with a date picker (or date range selector) and then a column with a select box that needs a strict comparison filter.

With this PR I would like to suggest a way to make filter plugins possible. Lets say I would like to make my own version of st-search that does a strict comparison. That's easy now, make your own directive based on st-search and change
```
var filter = ctrl.registerFilter('search');
```
into 
```
var filter = ctrl.registerFilter('myStrictFilter', true);
```
Maybe you would like to use a select box for selecting values in a range (\<10, 10-100, \>100), then
(example code, please don't copy)
```
var filter = ctrl.registerFilter('myRangeFilter', function(actual, expected){
  if (expected) {
    if (expected==='<10') {
      return actual < 10;
    }
    if (expected==='10-100') {
      return actual >=10 && actual <= 100;
    }
    if (expected==='>100') {
      return actual > 100;
    }
  }
 return true;
});
```

EDIT: This solution is now fully backwards compatible, no breaking changes to the API.

based on the Overpass API wiki, the Overpass QL of [completed ways and relations](http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Overpass_API/Advanced_examples) should be

> (
  node(50.746,7.154,50.748,7.157);
  <;
  >;
);
out meta;

This is a revival of  https://github.com/openfisca/openfisca-core/pull/378, but differently implemented, with the needed cache adaptation.

The idea is to allow a formula to take an extra parameter. For instance : 
```py
class ppa_fictive(Variable):
# (...)
def function(self, simulation, period, reference_period):

class ppa(Variable):
# (...)
simulation.calculate('ppa_fictive', period2, extra_params = [period])
```

The cache has been adapted so that is doesn't return a value cached for a specific set of extra parameters when called with a different one. In this case, the content of the cache would be:
```py
holder._array_by_period[period] = 
    { (param_value_1,) : result1, (param_value_2,) : result2 }
```
I slightly refactored it, trying to expose two clearly named methods to the outside : `put_in_cache(self, value, period, extra_params = None)` and `get_from_cache(self, period, extra_params = None)`.

I also adapted the conversion to JSON (here and in the API). 
```json
"ppa_fictive": {
    "2015-11": {
        "{reference_period: 2015-12}": 533.10595703125,
        "{reference_period: 2016-01}": 377.430419921875
    },
    "2015-10": {
        "{reference_period: 2015-12}": 428.10595703125,
        "{reference_period: 2016-01}": 272.430419921875
    },
    "2015-12": 283.0704345703125,
    "2015-09": 0
},
```
As long as there is only one result, for a variable and a period, there will be no difference with the actual behavior. The json will be more complex only if a formula has been called with two different set of extra parameters. This happens for instance with ppa if you compute it for several months in a row.

some joins were not unlocked (main reason), removed extra gains that were applied

This partly fixes stuff for https://github.com/bulletphysics/bullet3/pull/1308

See 'set_servo_target' call, that unlocks the motor, inside the first_torque_call condition:

https://github.com/openai/roboschool/blob/master/roboschool/cpp-household/physics-bullet.cpp#L502

if (first_torque_call) {
		set_servo_target(0, 0.1, 0.1, 0);
		first_torque_call = false;
	}

